<br>
My son, 5 at the time, heard the song so much over the next few days that he could sing it with me.  And I emailed Lee Greenwood, thanking him for writing a song that, while when he wrote it wouldn't hold a meaning for many that it does today, was still a wonderful song when it was released.  He sent me back an email (which still surprises me), and I still love to hear that song.  <br>
<br>
It's a very meaningful song, moreso after the events of a year ago.  And just remember everyone....They can't take that away...... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/udrackorespyritfyst.showPublicProfile?language=EN>DrackoreSpyritfyst</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Egging EW</span><br>  Posts: 409<br> <font color=#628CBC>(9/11/02 9:44:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=391.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember...</span><hr size=1> There isn't a lot more I can say that I haven't said before in many different &quot;tones&quot; regarding this subject.<br>
<br>
I was deployed in Saudi Arabia the day this happened, waiting to come home actually.  All flights in and out were cancelled and while I really wanted to get home to my son, I wasn't mad.  How could I be mad after so many people died?<br>
<br>
Then I saw the Saudi nationals.  Fine, upstanding people they were.  Kids and adults of all ages celebrating.  Made me sick to my stomach and made me wonder how the gate guards with the guns maintained enough composure to not blast the crap out of them.  I probably would have.<br>
<br>
I lost friends at the Pentagon and WTC a year ago.  Today is a very solemn day for me.  I find myself drained and just feeling completely &quot;blah&quot;.  I even called my ex-wife today so she could &quot;pick me up&quot;.  It sounds strange I know, but because of where I was and where she was, we did a lot of talking to make sure we were ok and such.<br>
<br>
Anyhow, I can't blame anyone for not wanting to watch the ceremonies today and I can respect your reasons.  I myself, though, feel pulled to watch.  Just hearing one friend's name will no doubt stir a lot up, but if I don't watch I probably will regret it.<br>
<br>
Peace and good will to you all.<br>
Pat<br>
