 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/ucereberial.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cereberial</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>QHills and Clueless</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#628CBC>(9/11/02 4:19:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=391.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember...</span><hr size=1>  Worked at 80 Pine Street about a 15 min walk from the World Trade Center. In retrospect, my memory is somewhat hazy and things have unfortunately been clarified by people telling me what happened.  <br>
<br>
- I remember hearing what I thought was an explosion, walking to the window and looking out to see the smoke. <br>
- I remember being told not to leave the building as we were safer inside than outside in the debris. <br>
- I remember running outside when the buildings crashed with the thought I would/might die. <br>
- I remember the feeling of being covered in dirt &amp; other debris, and after realizing I understand how people who go through war feel. <br>
- I remember hearing the loud noise of human bodies hitting the ground. (Don't know if I heard them, but I associate the nois of things hitting the ground with bodies after the fact.)<br>
- I remember the chaos of thousand of people fleeing the scene, while EMT, Police, Fireman rushed towards the building.<br>
- I remember spending a week at friends/co-workers houses since I couldn't get my car, and even if I could the bridges were virtually closed. <br>
- I remember the conversations I had while waiting 3 + hours on line to give blood. <br>
- I remember a month of funerals for friends, co-workers etc.<br>
<br>
All in All 9-11-2001 will live with me forever as the single scariest moment in my life. I promised that it would change me. I would help others, appreciate life, be a better person. I didn't change me. I'm still basically the same person I was, and the only difference is I work out of NJ now. (No more city tax = good).<br>
<br>
Ultimately the stories being told are a wonderful thing. It allows many to reflect back on this painful memory and try to recapture some of our dedicaiton to be become better. It allows us to reflect that on a day where most any sane person would have run away from what people thought was sure death, some people ran towards it, in doing so they sacrificed their own lives. Remember that hundreds of thousands of people were withint a few city blocks of that disaster, and only 3000 died, around 400 of those deaths were people trying to help out. To me, death is never a reason to celebrate, but heroism is. 400 people gave their life, so thousands can live. Sept 11, should be a national holiday to honour fireman, police officers everywhere.<br>
<br>
As a side note those same Fireman and Police officers have not received a raise in several years. A 1st year fireman qualifies for food stamps in NYC. <p>Cereberial Cortex<BR>Illusionist<BR>Desperate Measures<BR></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/ucereberial.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Cereberial</A> at: 9/11/02 4:25:08 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#102960><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub169.ezboard.com/ugrimmbaldisstormwolfe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grimmbaldis Stormwolfe</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Qeynos Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 22<br> <font color=#628CBC>(9/14/02 8:56:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=391.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Remember...</span><hr size=1> /bump<br>
